      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Ernest E. Neal (1911-1972) was one of the first African American foreign aid officers to work for the United States Agency 
	  for International Development (USAID).  For part of his career he was Special Assistant for Community Development and Chief of 
	  the Rural Development Division for 
	  its US Operations Mission to the Philippines and Deputy Director of USAID/Philippines.</p>
	  <p>For more information about Neal's work, see "South to South across the Pacific: Ernest E. Neal
      and Community Development Efforts in the American South and the Philippines," by Satoshi Sakano (2005).</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Ernest E. Neal Papers</emph> consist of reports relating to USAID's Rural Development efforts in 
		 the Philippines, as well as writings by Neal (speeches, addresses, and a printed booklet).</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Reports</emph> contains quarterly narrative progress reports, reports on two regional seminars, 
		 and a "Terminal Report" 
		 written in July of 1958.  There are also an assortment of later reports, including two brief summaries for the State 
		 Department, one "Monthly Report" (April l1966) and several papers on proposed education projects.</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Writings</emph> consists of a published booklet entitled "Men, Ideas and Institutions: The Keys to Development" and 
		 the typescripts of numerous speeches and addresses, including a keynote address given at the Philippine Association of 
		 Social Workers conference in 1956.</p></scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>Reports are in chronological order.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
